  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a financial crime that involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). The legal definitions of money laundering can vary slightly depending on the jurisdiction, but they generally encompass the following key elements:\n\n### United States\nUnder U.S. law, **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** defines money laundering as knowingly conducting or attempting to conduct a financial transaction involving the proceeds of specified unlawful activity (SUA) with the intent to:\n1. Promote the carrying on of the SUA.\n2. Engage in tax evasion or fraud.\n3. Conceal or disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of the proceeds of the SUA.\n\n**18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** further prohibits knowingly engaging in a monetary transaction involving criminally derived property valued at more than $10,000.\n\n### European Union\nIn the EU, money laundering is defined under **Directive (EU) 2018/1673** as:\n1. The conversion or transfer of property, knowing that such property is derived from criminal activity, for the purpose of concealing or disguising its illicit origin or assisting anyone involved in the commission of the crime to evade the legal consequences of their actions.\n2. The concealment or disguise of the true nature, source, location, disposition, movement, ownership, or rights with respect to property, knowing that such property is derived from criminal activity.\n3. The acquisition, possession, or use of property, knowing at the time of receipt that such property was derived from criminal activity.\n4. Participation in, association with, or attempts to commit any of the above acts.\n\n### United Kingdom\nUnder the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA)**, money laundering offenses include:\n1. Concealing, disguising, converting, transferring, or removing criminal property from the UK (Section 327).\n2. Entering into or becoming involved in an arrangement which facilitates the acquisition, retention, use, or control of criminal property by or on behalf of another person (Section 328).\n3. Acquiring, using, or possessing criminal property (Section 329).\n\n### United Nations\nThe **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** and the **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** define money laundering as:\n1. The conversion or transfer of property, knowing that such property is derived from any offense or offenses, for the purpose of concealing or disguising the illicit origin of the property or assisting any person who is involved in the commission of such an offense to evade the legal consequences of his or her action.\n2. The concealment or disguise of the true nature, source, location, disposition, movement, rights with respect to, or ownership of property, knowing that such property is derived from a criminal offense or offenses.\n\n### Common Elements Across Jurisdictions\nWhile the specific wording may differ, the legal definitions of money laundering generally include:\n1. **Knowledge or intent**: The person involved must know or should have known that the proceeds are derived from criminal activity.\n2. **Criminal proceeds**: The funds involved must originate from unlawful activities.\n3. **Purpose**: The transaction(s) must be conducted with the intent to conceal, disguise, or legitimize the illicit origin of the funds.\n\nMoney laundering is a serious crime globally, and jurisdictions often impose severe penalties, including fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment, for those convicted. Financial institutions and other regulated entities are typically required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious activities.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
